Earlier this week, a source sent me a depressing photo of a Tom Ford Beauty=
 makeup display=E2=80=94a gondola, in industry parlance=E2=80=94at a Sephor=
a in Union Square. In the image, the shelves were sparsely filled, and not =
a single Tom Ford =E2=80=9Cface=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cliquid lip=E2=80=9D te=
ster was in sight. It reminded me of the time I saw JLo Beauty stashed away=
 at the back of the store, covered in a literal film of dust. Alas, in beau=
ty retailing, an empty Sephora gondola usually means one thing=E2=80=A6

Yesterday, Lauren assessed ( https://puck.news/tom-ford-after-tom-ford/?utm=
_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F24%2F24%29&utm_content=3DLine+S=
heet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F24%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) the future of the Tom Ford b=
rand in the absence of Tom Ford, its exacting and visionary founder. As she
noted, the departure of Tom Ford creative director Peter Hawkings only one =
year after Est=C3=A9e Lauder Companies completed its multibillion-dollar ac=
quisition of the Tom Ford brand was only part of the story. =E2=80=9CEven i=
f Hawkings was difficult, and even if his wife was unusually close to the b=
usiness=E2=80=94and even if the clothes, themselves, weren=E2=80=99t sellin=
g=E2=80=94perhaps none of that would have mattered if the beauty and fragra=
nce business was on fire,=E2=80=9D she wrote. =E2=80=9CTom Ford is, and has=
 always been, a beauty brand first=E2=80=94all the way back to the launch o=
f the first fragrance, in 2006, which predated the clothes by a year. Alas,=
 it was not.=E2=80=9D

