Vanilla Sex

The descent of Tom Ford Beauty is apparent in its product names. =E2=80=9CF=
ucking Fabulous=E2=80=9D was the phenomenally successful scent that launche=
d in 2017, and yet =E2=80=9CVanilla Sex,=E2=80=9D which came out last year,=
 is like an SNL parody. This is likely the result of a series of subtle but=
 significant personnel changes. The brand=E2=80=99s executive director of e=
ditorial, involved in fragrance and makeup product names, stories, and posi=
tioning, left in 2020. John Demsey, the veteran Lauder executive and archit=
ect behind the Tom Ford arrangement, got ousted over an Instagram post in 2=
022. Then Ford stepped down following the sale to ELC.

To me, Lauder=E2=80=99s slowness to embrace TikTok as a marketing platform=
=E2=80=94an issue across their portfolio=E2=80=94was especially obvious at =
Tom Ford, which failed to capitalize on viral products such as Soleil Lip
Blush, a $62 lip balm with gold flecks. This probably could have resulted i=
n years of relevance in their makeup category=E2=80=93=E2=80=93as we have s=
een with other luxury viral lip products such as Dior=E2=80=99s lip oil. Th=
ere=E2=80=99s also skincare, where there hasn=E2=80=99t been a new product =
launch in years, and I=E2=80=99m told that Lauder has steadily been reducin=
g distribution since 2022. I=E2=80=99ve previously reported that ELC C.E.O.=
 Fabrizio Freda=E2=80=99s blanket approach to product=E2=80=93=E2=80=93i.e.=
, forcing makeup brands to do skincare=E2=80=93=E2=80=93has mostly backfire=
d. An audacious makeup and fragrance brand launching a $450 =E2=80=9Ccreme =
concentrate=E2=80=9D? Come on.

Back in 2018, I remember Ford telling me it took some cajoling to get Laude=
r to print =E2=80=9CFucking Fabulous=E2=80=9D on a bottle (conservative mar=
kets had watered-down versions that only implied profanity). That may be tr=
ue, but even if Ford were still involved today, I=E2=80=99m not sure we wou=
ld have gotten another Black Orchid or Fucking Fabulous
fragrance, or a new makeup with the hype of the brand=E2=80=99s original li=
psticks. Arguably, it was Demsey=E2=80=99s exit that left Tom Ford Beauty e=
xposed. Without him, there=E2=80=99s no longer a dual corporate and brand-f=
orward counterpart aligned with Ford=E2=80=99s vision who is also willing t=
o be the intermediary with a CPG-minded Freda. Hard to imagine Demsey or Fo=
rd approving Vanilla Sex in a million years, either.

That=E2=80=99s it from Rachel and me. P.S., on this Hodinkee news ( https:/=
