             <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Yes, or should I=
 say <i>alas</i>, Tom Ford=E2=80=99s makeup business is facing serious head=
winds at Sephora, the almighty LVMH-owned beauty chain. According to one pe=
rson familiar with Sephora=E2=80=99s business, sales of Tom Ford Beauty mak=
eup products are down almost 50 percent at the chain year to date. =E2=80=
=9CNew makeup gondolas are literally rolling out this month,=E2=80=9D accor=
ding to an executive with knowledge of Sephora=E2=80=99s business. But that=
 doesn=E2=80=99t change the fact that the brand has seen its relevance in c=
osmetics slip. <br/><br/>There was a time when Tom Ford lipsticks were a re=
velation. If you remember, the brand started as a licensing agreement with =
the debut of Black Orchid, a perfume, in 2006, and expanded into makeup and=
 skincare in 2010 and 2019, respectively. Then there was Lips &amp; Boys li=
p color, the Soleil makeup, and the Shade and Illuminate
contour palette.<br/><br/>Sure, one could blame <b>Guillaume Jesel</b>, the=
 president and C.E.O. of Tom Ford. But in reality, the brand=E2=80=99s setb=
acks are merely microcosms of the <i>larger </i>problems=E2=80=94lackluster=
 product innovation, the mishandling of the North American business, etcete=
ra=E2=80=94afflicting parentco ELC, which just announced that <b>Akhil</b> =
<b>Shrivastava</b> will succeed longtime C.F.O. <b>Tracey Thomas Travis</b>=
, who plans to retire next year. Meanwhile, amid a massive restructuring, t=
he company is in the process of laying off <i>thousands</i> of employees, w=
hile the stock price has dropped to a seven-year low. (A spokesperson for T=
he Est=C3=A9e Lauder Companies declined to comment.)<br/> <br/>Lauder=E2=80=
=99s brands have <i>long</i> struggled at Sephora, according to a source wi=
th knowledge of the retailer=E2=80=99s business, with the exception of The =
Ordinary and Too Faced. (Sources close to Sephora confirmed that Clinique m=
akeup is exiting the retailer and that Bobbi
Brown=E2=80=99s door count is being reduced, too.) According to a Sephora i=
nsider, this is the result of a =E2=80=9Cperfect storm=E2=80=9D=E2=80=93=E2=
=80=93a mashup of Sephora=E2=80=99s penchant for showcasing limited or excl=
usive products, and Lauder=E2=80=99s own shortcomings when it comes to unde=
rstanding and supporting a Sephora business. =E2=80=9CLauder has no idea ho=
w to win in Sephora. They ignored Sephora as an important channel and what =
it meant. No one tried to understand and unlock it=E2=80=94outside of Too F=
aced, which grew up there,=E2=80=9D this person said. Tom Ford=E2=80=99s fr=
agrance business, however, is faring better. The category is strong, accord=
ing to four insiders. (A spokesperson for Sephora declined to comment.) <br=
/><br/>A former Lauder executive offered a more poignant assessment. At a c=
onglomerate like Lauder, individual brands can lose their ability to manage=
 their presentation in various markets. =E2=80=9CIn North America, brands h=
ave very little power to actually direct or even defend some of the decisio=
ns being
made,=E2=80=9D they explained to me. =E2=80=9CTom Ford had success in makeu=
p in China=E2=80=93=E2=80=93probably not at the level of fragrances, but it=
